    "summary": "The Battle of Berlin was the final major offensive of [[event:112|World War II]] in Europe, fought from April 16 to May 2, 1945. Soviet forces under marshals Georgy Zhukov, Ivan Konev, and Konstantin Rokossovsky converged on the German capital from the east, with over two million troops, 6,000 tanks, and 45,000 artillery pieces. German defenders, including regular army units, Waffen-SS formations, Hitler Youth, and elderly Home Guard, fought desperate rearguard actions but were overwhelmed by the Soviet onslaught.\n\nAdolf Hitler remained in Berlin until the end, conducting the final stages of the war from his underground bunker beneath the Reich Chancellery. On April 30, as Soviet troops fought street-by-street through the city, Hitler committed suicide together with Eva Braun, whom he had married the day before. Their bodies were burned in the Chancellery garden. The German garrison surrendered on May 2. General Alfred Jodl signed Germany's unconditional surrender at Reims on May 7, with a ceremonial ratification in Berlin on May 8 — celebrated as V-E Day (Victory in Europe Day).\n\nThe battle resulted in catastrophic casualties on both sides: Soviet losses numbered approximately 80,000 dead, while German military deaths were immense and civilian losses substantial. The city itself was massively damaged. The victory ended nearly six years of war in Europe and marked the complete destruction of the [[event:2653|Nazi state]] that had unleashed unprecedented violence across the continent.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Berlin",
